  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Money Laundering Suppression Act of 1994\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Criminalize money laundering activities\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establish reporting requirements for cash transactions over $10,000\n- Impose civil and criminal penalties for violations\n\n3. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation\n\n4. International Cooperation:\n- Compliance with Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Information sharing with international law enforcement agencies\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent, detect, and prosecute money laundering activities by establishing comprehensive legal frameworks and reporting requirements for financial institutions and businesses.",
